with the clothing my elders require me to wear (in front of them). Their idea of my correct dress is different than mine. I wear my jilbabs and abayas, and sometimes they ask me to cover my arms and legs. I think it’s a stretch because these are full-length pants or abaya, but if they require me to cover off, I cover off. I silently damn the sun of my country and don’t allow my mutilated body to burn under the sun rays.

I am 19 and my problem is what will the people say? I come from an Asian background, which means as soon as a guy glances at you he’s thinking of « touching » you. But I also come from a Muslim background and Muslim men don’t give you that chance. Religion and culture in the incorrect combination produce a domino effect of problems.

The day I got married was the happiest day of my life. I was so complete in mind and my happiness filled the whole house. As for the problems that accompanied the marriage, they weren’t more than ten minutes of the total time span of the event. The most important one, however, was that I discovered my fun-loving husband is not as flawless as I wished. He is a person who switches between extreme reactions to any situation, he sneaked off once and was told he stayed out till morning in several streets away, and even drank.
